<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="370">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181838" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole amazonica Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole amazonica Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">Pheidole amazonica</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="370">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="370">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181838" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole amazonica Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole amazonica Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">amazonica</taxonomicName>
, a reference to the geographical region of origin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="370">
diagnosis A small, brown member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group most similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181873" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavifrons Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavifrons Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">flavifrons</taxonomicName>
but also in various traits to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33595" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arhuaca">arhuaca</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181913" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole nitidicollis Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole nitidicollis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">nitidicollis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34045" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tenerescens Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tenerescens Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenerescens">tenerescens</taxonomicName>
, differing from those species and other members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group by the following combination of traits. Major: dorsal half of the posterior head surface in profile flat; occipital margin in full-face view deeply and broadly concave; propodeal spines directed to the rear, not vertical to the basal propodeal face; an indistinct, circular brown spot present on vertex; a patch of rugoreticulum present laterad to each antennal fossa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="370">Minor: propodeal spines directed backward; humerus in dorsal-oblique view denticulate; occiput narrowed but lacking a nuchal collar; postpetiole from above bell-shaped.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="370">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.78, HL 0.78, SL 0.40, EL 0.08, PW 0.38. Paratype minor: HW 0.42, HL 0.44, SL 0.38, EL 0.08, PW 0.26.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="370">color Major: body medium brown, with dark brown circular spot on vertex, and anterior one-fourth of head capsule dark yellowish brown; appendages dark yellowish brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="370">Minor: body mostly medium brown, with sides of pronotum, nodes of petiole and postpetiole, and first gastral tergite light brown; appendages also light brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="370">Range Known from the type locality and near Tena, Napo, Ecuador, 600 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="370">
biology At the type locality in Peru, Stefan Cover (unpublished collection notes) found 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181838" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole amazonica Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole amazonica Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">amazonica</taxonomicName>
to be apparently the most abundant of all 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
species, ranging from terra firme forest into seasonally flooded forest and nesting in rotten sticks or branches on the forest floor. Colonies contained several hundred workers and a single queen. No seed caches were found in any of the 21 nests dissected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
